    {
      "id": "fhe_register_key_section",
      "role": "paper_section_context",
      "path": "research/fhe/paper/sections/05c_register_key_selection.tex",
      "required": true,
      "exists": true,
      "bytes": 4014,
      "sha256": "687dd6a56b69d330f9d48e51df28168d10b4bff8161f8196439afd21198f388e",
      "status": "loaded",
      "text_summary": {
        "line_count": 30,
        "needle_hits": [
          {
            "line": 1,
            "text": "\\section{Register-Key Selection and Row-Aware Incidence}"
          },
          {
            "line": 2,
            "text": "\\label{sec:register-key-selection}"
          },
          {
            "line": 4,
            "text": "The K900-native collision census in Section~\\ref{sec:k900-native-collision-bound} gives the Track A result: within the K900 carrier, the target predicate selects exactly three base cycles and six oriented presentations. The present section "
          },
          {
            "line": 6,
            "text": "The starting point is the register-boundary audit summarized in Section~\\ref{sec:register-boundary}. Endpoint labels, shared edge order, bare \\(G_{15}\\) isomorphism, and the K900 odd/even triangle partition do not force a unique chamber reg"
          },
          {
            "line": 8,
            "text": "A census of the K900-to-theorem-object key space gives \\(120\\) candidate graph isomorphisms. Public chamber/triangle predicates reduce this space to \\(60\\) structured keypairs. Each keypair is explained by a Petersen line-graph involution: "
          },
